docs.lead_paragraph: We journalists don’t always pay enough attention to good news. So I want to highlight some this morning: Across much of the United States and Europe, the coronavirus has been spreading less rapidly than many people feared.

docs.abstract: A variety of events have gone digital this year — and they’re joined by the marquee Global Pride livestream.
docs.snippet: A variety of events have gone digital this year — and they’re joined by the marquee Global Pride livestream.
docs.lead_paragraph: If you’re feeling conflicted about how to celebrate Pride this year, you’re hardly alone. Three months after the coronavirus pandemic turned the world on its head, America has been rocked by coast-to-coast protests inspired by George Floyd, whose death has led millions to cry out for an end to police brutality — and an end to police departments generally.

headline.main: Celebrate Pride With Town Halls and Club Beats
headline.print_headline: Celebrate Pride With Town Halls And Club Beats

docs.abstract: With newfound momentum on social justice causes, players around the league have many opinions on what comes next. But most agree that the N.F.L. must recognize Colin Kaepernick.
docs.snippet: With newfound momentum on social justice causes, players around the league have many opinions on what comes next. But most agree that the N.F.L. must recognize Colin Kaepernick.
docs.lead_paragraph: In the wake of the killing of George Floyd in Minneapolis, the N.F.L., a league that has wrestled with racial issues for years, has shown unusual unity. Players, coaches, league officials and owners have expressed sadness, remorse and a commitment to seek solutions to police violence against African-American people and other forms of social injustice.

headline.main: The N.F.L. Embraces Progressive Action, but Not Yet Kaepernick
headline.print_headline: N.F.L. Embraces Calls for Justice, but Not Yet Kaepernick

docs.abstract: He is the only African-American driver in NASCAR’s top-flight racing series, and this week got the organization to bar the Confederate flag at its events.
docs.snippet: He is the only African-American driver in NASCAR’s top-flight racing series, and this week got the organization to bar the Confederate flag at its events.
docs.lead_paragraph: Bubba Wallace, who instigated NASCAR’s banning of the Confederate flag, is the racing series’ only black driver. That has put him in the spotlight in a sport whose owners, drivers, crews and fans have historically been predominantly white.

headline.print_headline: A Black Driver Steps Into the Spotlight

docs.lead_paragraph: WASHINGTON — President Trump and his aides spent much of Wednesday trying to rewrite history, claiming that Mr. Trump was merely “inspecting” a bunker last week during riots over the death of George Floyd and insisting falsely that peaceful protesters near the White House were attacking the police when the authorities used chemical agents to make them move so that Mr. Trump could have his picture taken at a nearby church.
